The fire sometime <br>
A new U.S. commitment to a fusion power reactor<br>
<br>
BY JANET RAE-DUPREE<br>
<br>
It's been a long time coming, and it has a long way to go. But a tantalizing possibility for limitless clean electricity–nuclear fusion–inched closer to reality last week when the Bush administration said the United States will rejoin efforts to build the International Thermonuclear Experimental Reactor. <br>
<br>
 While today's nuclear plants split uranium atoms, creating radioactive waste, fusion slams together light atoms at millions of degrees and leaves inert byproducts. Lab prototypes that suspend super-heated gas in doughnut-shaped magnetic fields have yielded energy, but not enough to sustain the reactions. If it works, the $5 billion ITER–iter is Latin for &quot;the way&quot;–would exceed break-even and test potential power-plant technologies.<br>
<br>
Planning has been underway for 16 years, but the United States withdrew in 1998 when the construction budget swelled to over $10 billion. Since then, the multinational ITER (pronounced eater) group–including Japan, Russia, Europe, Canada, and China–has halved the projected cost. Last week Energy Secretary Spencer Abraham said that the United States would contribute 10 percent of the cost, while continuing fusion research at home. He noted that besides being clean and safe, &quot;Fusion plants could produce hydrogen . . . to power hundreds of millions of hydrogen fuel cell vehicles.&quot; <br>
<br>
At ITER meetings this month in St. Petersburg, Russia, the project team plans to divide up the development work. Canada, Japan, France, and Spain are all bidding to host the reactor, which could be functioning by 2014. After that, it would be at least 25 years before fusion energy is on the power grid. <br>
<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
ITER would be a big step forward in another one of the greatest intellectual and engineering endeavors of human history. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=dustyslaunchpad>Dustys Launchpad</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Space Cadet</span><br>  Posts: 46<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(2/2/03 9:50 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm25.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=124.topic&index=1>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/posticons/radman.gif" align=absmiddle>  Silly question</span><hr size=1> Probabally a silly question.<br>
<br>
Where is the Tritium to come from in a commercial power plant. I know that the idea is to breed Tritium from Lithium but we would ISTM have to capture *every* single Neutron generated by the Fusion process. in practice there would be a shortfall. How will this shortfall be overcome?<br>
<br>
Dusty <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=nuclaeon>Nuclaeon</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>NERVA Spaceplane Pilot</span><br>  Posts: 106<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(2/2/03 1:04 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm25.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=124.topic&index=2>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/posticons/radman.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: Silly question</span><hr size=1> Although I'm not exactly sure, you would need a tritium blanket around the plasma.  You cannot capture every neutron, but only a fraction of them because the reactor would have to be refeuled every few minutes.  You can always use other neutron emitting sources to induce the reaction with lithium.  I'll get back to you on this as I know exactly who to ask. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=zentrander>Zentrander</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Orion Commander</span><br>  Posts: 295<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(2/2/03 1:09 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm25.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=124.topic&index=3>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/posticons/radman.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: Silly question</span><hr size=1> probably going to sound silly but:<br>
<br>
as the fusion process is better understood and perfected, wont we be able to develop new fuels and materials?  Im sure the fuels we use today will be archaic compared to the things they do further down the line. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=nuclaeon>Nuclaeon</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>NERVA Spaceplane Pilot</span><br>  Posts: 107<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(2/2/03 1:47 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm25.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=124.topic&index=4>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/posticons/radman.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: Silly question</span><hr size=1> Materials: yes.  <br>
Fuels: kind of, but not really.<br>
<br>
The reasons lie in the laws of physics.  We already know from detailed calculations and experiments, the energy released from just about every nuclear reaction and how difficult it is to fuse them.<br>
<br>
The best fusion fuel is Deuterium and Helium-3, giving the largest energy yield of any fusion reaction.  The problem is you need a lot more energy than D-T to fuse them.  That's the main reason why D-T is researched heavily, it is the easiest fuel to fuse. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=dustyslaunchpad>Dustys Launchpad</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Space Cadet</span><br>  Posts: 48<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(2/2/03 3:00 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm25.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=124.topic&index=5>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/posticons/radman.gif" align=absmiddle>  re silly question</span><hr size=1> D-He3 is hampererd as a significant power source since I believe He3 is rare on earth and (AIUI) it cannot be synthesised (I believe it has been found on the moon but there can't be that much of it there) from a power plant point of view I would have thought D-D would have advantages since the oceians contain a *vast* amount of D and the reaction produces no neutrons and therefore no radioactivity. the down side is that we need a lot more trigger energy to initiate D-D fusion than we do for D-T.<br>
<br>
As for processes that generate a controlled source of neutrons for breeding lithium, are there any other than fission?<br>
<br>
the problem with using U235 fission is that (assuming a 60% capture ratio) each fission will only produce 1 tritium but each fission will produce over 10 times as much energy as a D-T fusion IE even if we are only having to make up as little as a 10% neutron shortfall the Fission *feeder* plant will produce as much power as the fusion main reactor this could dampen the enthusiasim somewhat.<br>
<br>
